          "_name": "content2",
          "_customHTML": "<section class=\"mbr-section article content1\">\n\n    <mbr-parameters>\n    <!-- Block parameters controls (Blue \"Gear\" panel) -->\n        <input type=\"range\" inline title=\"Top\" name=\"paddingTop\" min=\"0\" max=\"8\" step=\"1\" value=\"4\">\n        <input type=\"range\" inline title=\"Bottom\" name=\"paddingBottom\" min=\"0\" max=\"8\" step=\"1\" value=\"4\">\n        <input type=\"color\" title=\"Background Color\" name=\"bgColor\" value=\"#ffffff\">\n    <!-- End block parameters -->\n    </mbr-parameters> \n\n    <div class=\"container\">\n        <div class=\"media-container-row\">\n            <div class=\"mbr-text col-12 col-md-8 mbr-fonts-style\" mbr-theme-style=\"display-7\" data-multiline mbr-article>\n                <blockquote><b>In this article, I am reviewing “Race-Making and the Nation State” by Anthony W. Marx, which analyses the state’s role in the construction of race. Marx compares the cases of Brazil, South Africa, and the United States. All three went through processes of state configuration in the aftermath of slavery but with very different outcomes. South Africa and the United States emerged with distinct official racial ideologies - the former with Apartheid, the latter with Jim Crow. In contrast, Brazil never created legal distinctions based on race.&nbsp;</b></blockquote>\n            </div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</section>",
