          "_name": "content1",
          "_customHTML": "<section class=\"mbr-section article content1\">\n    \n    <mbr-parameters>\n    <!-- Block parameters controls (Blue \"Gear\" panel) -->\n        <input type=\"range\" inline title=\"Top\" name=\"paddingTop\" min=\"0\" max=\"8\" step=\"1\" value=\"4\">\n        <input type=\"range\" inline title=\"Bottom\" name=\"paddingBottom\" min=\"0\" max=\"8\" step=\"1\" value=\"4\">\n        <input type=\"color\" title=\"Background Color\" name=\"bgColor\" value=\"#ffffff\">\n    <!-- End block parameters -->\n    </mbr-parameters> \n\n    <div class=\"container\">\n        <div class=\"media-container-row\">\n            <div class=\"mbr-text col-12 col-md-8 mbr-fonts-style\" mbr-theme-style=\"display-7\" data-app-selector=\".mbr-text\" data-multiline mbr-article><p>Past explanations do not provide a full answer to why Brazil did not institutionalize racism. It is often said that Brazil was more tolerant of its slaves- they were allowed to own private property, marry, and buy their freedom. This rights bely the fact that slaves lives were not necessarily better than those of slaves in other countries. For instance, slave mortality in Brazil was higher than other slave powers due to the harsh conditions slaves were subjected to. \n</p><p></p><div><br></div><div>It is also believed that the high level of miscegenation in Brazil provided for a greater social mobility among races. But in practice only a few could advance socially, this was enough however to create a belief in mobility (Marx, 1996: 187). Moreover, it is been proven that the United States and South Africa were also significantly miscegenated societies, so this is not a differentiating factor between the nations.\n</div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div>Economic explanations have suggested that segregation served the interests of Capital by providing cheap black labor, while simultaneously ensuring higher-paid white labor (Marx, 1996: 187). In actuality, racial hierarchies primarily served to provide stability and lessen the potential for class conflict between white people, and led the state to impose racial domination in South Africa and the United States and give privilege to white workers in Brazil. Even if economic development was enhanced by racism, it does not explain the creation of a racial order by itself.\n</div><div><br></div><p></p></div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</section>",
