          "_name": "content1",
          "_customHTML": "<section class=\"mbr-section article content1\">\n    \n    <mbr-parameters>\n    <!-- Block parameters controls (Blue \"Gear\" panel) -->\n        <input type=\"range\" inline title=\"Top\" name=\"paddingTop\" min=\"0\" max=\"8\" step=\"1\" value=\"4\">\n        <input type=\"range\" inline title=\"Bottom\" name=\"paddingBottom\" min=\"0\" max=\"8\" step=\"1\" value=\"4\">\n        <input type=\"color\" title=\"Background Color\" name=\"bgColor\" value=\"#ffffff\">\n    <!-- End block parameters -->\n    </mbr-parameters> \n\n    <div class=\"container\">\n        <div class=\"media-container-row\">\n            <div class=\"mbr-text col-12 col-md-8 mbr-fonts-style\" mbr-theme-style=\"display-7\" data-app-selector=\".mbr-text\" data-multiline mbr-article><p>Marx believes that, in all three cases, it was the consolidation of a post-abolition or united state that gave rise to the dilemma of whether and how to incorporate those of African descent (Marx, 1996: 192). \n</p><p><span style=\"font-size: 1rem;\">After the Boer War in South Africa, segregation of black people became a key tool for reconciling the differences between British and Afrikaners.  In order to create the South African State, white unity became fundamental. It was even further encouraged in 1948 when Apartheid was imposed.&nbsp;</span><br></p><p></p><div><span style=\"font-size: 1rem;\">A similar thing happened in the US after the Civil War freed the slaves. Despite the fact that black people were now free, the North and the South continued to foster racial domination out of fear of another Southern rebellion (Marx, 1996: 196). The expansion of black people newfound rights was quickly abandoned as Jim Crow segregation was spread throughout the South (Marx, 1996: 196).&nbsp;</span><br></div><div><br></div><div><span style=\"font-size: 1rem;\">It is true that the cases of South Africa and the United States have deep differences. In the US, rights existed but were not respected. Meanwhile, in South Africa, rights were not guaranteed by the Constitution. However, the outcomes were similar. Conflict among white people was appeased with legal discrimination of black people. &nbsp;</span></div><div><span style=\"font-size: 1rem;\"><br></span></div><div><span style=\"font-size: 1rem;\">The case of Brazil makes for an interesting comparison. Portuguese colonialism imposed a more direct rule, maintaining unified elites. Therefore, there was no need for official racial discrimination. In order to avoid ethnic conflict during the transition from a colony to a state, an image of inclusiveness was created. Class mobility was encouraged through miscegenation in order to unite and “whiten” the population, counteracting the continued racial inequality (Marx, 1996: 199).</span></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><p></p></div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</section>",
