          "_name": "content1",
          "_customHTML": "<section class=\"mbr-section article content1\">\n    \n    <mbr-parameters>\n    <!-- Block parameters controls (Blue \"Gear\" panel) -->\n        <input type=\"range\" inline title=\"Top\" name=\"paddingTop\" min=\"0\" max=\"8\" step=\"1\" value=\"4\">\n        <input type=\"range\" inline title=\"Bottom\" name=\"paddingBottom\" min=\"0\" max=\"8\" step=\"1\" value=\"4\">\n        <input type=\"color\" title=\"Background Color\" name=\"bgColor\" value=\"#ffffff\">\n    <!-- End block parameters -->\n    </mbr-parameters> \n\n    <div class=\"container\">\n        <div class=\"media-container-row\">\n            <div class=\"mbr-text col-12 col-md-8 mbr-fonts-style\" mbr-theme-style=\"display-7\" data-app-selector=\".mbr-text\" data-multiline mbr-article><p><br></p><p><span style=\"font-size: 1rem;\">I</span><span style=\"font-size: 1rem;\">n the long run, racial exclusion beneficial to white people encouraged black solidarity and gave rise to black mobilization in South Africa and the United States. In Brazil, since there were not explicit state policies discriminating against black people, there was little mobilization. &nbsp;</span><br></p><p></p><div>Black-white conflict replaced intrawhite conflict, and institutionalized racism began to threaten national unity and stability. The Costs were suddenly higher than benefits, leading to states removing their discriminatory policies. Apartheid and Jim Crow eventually ended. \n</div><div><br></div><div>Marx concludes that the state is the central actor in race-making. It is the state that categorizes people as black, white, or mulatto, and enforces legal discrimination. Who is included and excluded is not random. Racism was purposefully created in order to stabilize a nation that had groups with potential conflict. Nonetheless, once constructed, race can not be easily dismantled (Marx, 1996, p.207). Mobilization might have forced the nation-state to reconstruct itself is a more inclusive manner, but discrimination still exists today.</div><div><b><br></b></div><p></p></div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</section>",
